body:
## For Future Reference :zap:

I strongly recommend learning the new version of Javascript - ES6 (ECMAScript 6). It has been officially approved and is widely adopted by programmers. Popular frameworks like Angular 2, React, etc. all prioritize ES6 syntax.

ES6 introduces new syntax/concepts, such as:
- `let` / `const` variables
- Arrow functions, eg:
  ```
  let foo = () => {
    // operations
  };
  ```
- Module import
- `Promise` - a new method to deal with asynchronous task (instead of the old callback function)
- New way to implement Classes, eg:
  ```
  class Foo {
    constructor(num) {
      this.num = num;
    }

    addNum(a) {
      return this.num += a;
    }
  }
  ```
- And many more... :star2:

### Resources :books
- [ES6 - JavaScript Improved @Udacity](https://www.udacity.com/course/es6-javascript-improved--ud356)
- [Beginners ES6 and Babel Tutorial @HTML5 Hive](https://html5hive.org/es6-and-babel-tutorial/)
- [ECMAScript 6 Tutorial by ccoenraets](http://ccoenraets.github.io/es6-tutorial/)

Note that ES6 is usually used with Babel compiler (and a build process, such as `webpack`, `gulp`, etc.) for browser compatability fallback. So you will also learn about them in the resources above.
